  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010632.html"><b>Raids
    on Solusek Ro</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: Peak hours: Over 100
    people in Oasis and SK, over 90 people in Lake of Ill Omen, over 80 people
    in Overthere,.....]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    And many other zones that support the same level ranges that are near empty.
    You cant make a case for a &quot;crowded server&quot; by quoting the number
    of people in an overly populated zone. We could probably remove 500 people
    from peak, and those three zones would probably have roughly the same number
    of people in them.<br>
    <br>
    Simply, the zones are crowded because people would rather go to them (even
    with them being crowded) than somewhere else that isnt. There are plenty of
    areas for people who want to go places that arent crowded.<br>
    <br>
    Thats not to say that population on SolRo *isnt* above where it should be.
    When we bring up the next split server well certainly look at SolRo as a
    potential candidate. However, there certainly *are* things to do that do not
    involve crowds on that server. After all, it is less crowded than some
    servers were pre-Kunark, and now theres many more zones out there.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010679.html"><b>Back
    Stab Broken?</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: I dont think this is
    right - why should one weapon with exactly the same ration be a much more
    horrible backstab over something else with the exact same ratio?]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    Youve answered your own question in your post: Because the damage of the
    weapon is all that is used in calculating damage from a backstab, and the
    delay isnt taken into account. What youve described above is how backstab is
    designed to work, and it works correctly given that design. Indeed, a higher
    damage weapon of a given ratio, backstabs included, will typicaly do more
    damage than a lower damage weapon with a delay of the same ratio.<br>
    <br>
    Of course we could get into damage bonuses on the primary melee slot and how
    they affect damage output, favoring the faster weapons, however I would
    imagine that two points of damage would offset that.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010685.html"><b>Ranger
    Issue Dead</b></a><br>
