<ul>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010504.html"><b>Camping,
    Nerfs</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: Well guess what Abashi,
    the nerfs have only created more problems than fixed, with out things to
    solo, noone can do anything without a group and when all of teh groups
    everywhere are saying &quot;I am full&quot; then I WANT MY MONEY BACK! I pay
    to play this game not to sit around for hours begging to play from people i
    do not even know or people i do not even PAY TO PLAY!]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    Hello again Robert,<br>
    <br>
    I hope that youll appreciate my being blunt. Im not really sure that I can
    tell you. The groups &quot;everywhere&quot; are not saying &quot;I am
    full&quot;. The groups in 3 areas in the game, known to be heavily camped,
    are telling you &quot;I am full&quot;. You might consider going someplace
    that isnt known to be heavily camped. You might consider trying to form a
    group of your own.<br>
    <br>
    Also, considering that you are level 48, do you not have any friends online
    who will invite you to their group? For instance, most people jump on line,
    check the friends list, find out where everyone is, and go join a friend. Do
    you not have any friends who make room and time for you?<br>
    <br>
    Last week you chose to do something very dangerous without the support of
    friends or a cleric and were upset when you died. This week you chose to go
    to 3 areas famous for being crowded/camped. You keep choosing to set
    yourself up for failure, and then cast blame upon the game.<br>
    <br>
    The game is designed to punish people who run into dangerous areas
    ill-prepared. The game is supposed to motivate people to go places less
    crowded with more opportunities by only supporting so many people in a given
    area. The game is supposed to reward people for making friends who will bend
    over backwards for them.<br>
    <br>
    The game is working fine in the situations that youve brought up. The best
    advice that I can offer is that you step outside the box and try doing
    something different from what &quot;everyone else&quot; does. I think that
    if you look around, you can probably find other people who went to Lower Guk,
    Karnors, and Rathe Mountains that night and had the same problem that you
    did. Try hooking up with those folks and going someplace else.<br>
    <br>
    On a slightly different note, make friends with people. Go out of your way
    to help others out. Theyll remember it, and will make room for you when you
    need a hand. So often I hear from people who primarily solo from 1 to 50 or
    so and then get upset that no one will group with them for the harder
    encounters. No one wants to walk into a level 40+ dungeon with someone who
    is having their first dungeon experience. Grouping skills and relationships
    are formed early on.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
