  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010321.html"><b>Items
    Missing After Patch</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: 1. How on earth do such
    things happen? What sort of baroque database design would allow character
    attributes (name, level, skills, etc.) to be retained, while
    &quot;forgetting&quot; all possessions?]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    One of the good (and bad) things about running a system with 300K users is
    that if we have a problem on our end, its never just one person experiences
    it. Ive never heard of this happening before. My first guess at what may
    have happened is that someone your friend gave his login info to took the
    stuff and destroyed anything NODROP. Every case of a wiped character that I
    am aware of could be tracked back to this with enough effort.<br>
    <br>
    In any case, though Ive never heard of it before, GMs still need to
    investigate every claim that they receive and act on them in short order.<br>
    <br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: Whats worse, his first
    responses from /petitions have been, &quot;itll take up to four weeks to
    research this and possibly restore your items, and anything you gain between
    now and then will be lost.&quot;]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    Im dismayed to hear that any GM would say anything of that nature since they
    all know that immediate investigations and responses are mandated by company
    policy. Please have your friend forward the GMs name to gscotto@verant.com
    along with a description of events.<br>
    <br>
    I think that Ive answered all of the questions youve posed in this thread.
    Please let me know if you need more info.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010018.html"><b>Roleplaying
    Server</b></a><br>
    We cannot enforce a roleplay server. Left unenforced, the environment on
    that server would be no different than any other server.<br>
    <br>
    I think that its the second sentence that you disagree with, but that is all
    there is to it. Roleplaying is a personal choice that everyone makes. If
    people wanting hardcore roleplay were to stick to their guns and do nothing
    but on any server out there, they might be able to turn peer pressure in
    their direction. However if they wont do it on a normal server, theres no
    reason to suggest that theyd do it on a server labled as a &quot;roleplay&quot;
    server.<br>
    <br>
    Furthermore, any new server is going to attract a large and diverse number
    of people regardless of any label on the server. It would also definitely
    attract the people who would go there just to give the roleplayers a hard
    time.<br>
    <br>
    Im sorry that you dont agree, but the issue closed. Like melee binding and
    experience systems, this is as firm as it gets.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008882.html"><b>Necro
    Nerfs Make Gamer Easier?</b></a><br>
    Itchy,<br>
    <br>
    Youre grasping at straws here. Please read the quote again:<br>
    <br>
    &quot;neither I nor other members of the tuning team actively seek out ways
    to make the lives of the players more difficult.&quot;<br>
    <br>
    We dont sit around trying to come up with ways to make the LIVES of the
    players more difficult. We dont have discussions about the best way to go
    about upsetting the players. We address issues in game. If theres an
    imbalance, well fix it. We fix it because gameplay mechanics must be
    balanced in order for the game to be challenging. If it werent challenging,
    no one would play.<br>
    <br>
    Sure, this means that certain aspects of the game are made more difficult in
    nature. An encounter might become harder to overcome. A weapon that does far
    too much damage may be weakened. A pathing issue that allows people to
    slaugther without risk will be fixed. Though these things might make one
    particular aspect of gameplay more difficult in nature, that doesnt
    translate to making the LIVES of the player more difficult.<br>
    <br>
    Changing an aspect of gameplay in a way that has no positive side makes the
    LIVES of the players difficult. The &quot;necro nerfs&quot; that you mention
    in the subject certainly had a positive side, and doesnt qualify.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
