  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010205.html"><b>Pending
    God Changes</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: Anybody who did not buy
    Kunark would be losing<br>
    a feature they always had, the ability to go on<br>
    raids on the planes and face down the Gods.]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    Not really, there is nothing to say that they cant participate in one form
    or another. But even if we assume that what you are saying is basically
    true, they are losing the ability to kill an NPC named &quot;XXX&quot;.
    Thats basically it.<br>
    <br>
    Heres the situation. The deities and dragons are meant to be top level
    encounters. We made an exception with Vox and Nagafen and kept them where
    they were even though the level cap went up. In order to do this, we had to
    place the level restriction on those encounters.<br>
    <br>
    The same situation is present with the deities, and the solution that we
    have is a compromise. Vox and Nagafen remained the same yet higher level
    folks cant attack them, and the deities will increase in power, so the lower
    level folks wont be able to attack them. At the same time we are taking the
    loot from the current deities and moving it to NPCs that are equivalent in
    power to the current deities.<br>
    <br>
    Leaving things as they are now is not a reasonable option. This is the best
    option available to us.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/010202.html"><b>CS
    Question</b></a><br>
    <font color="#072876"><i>[Quote from original post: I know it is within your
    power to create and return the items I have lost (some of which no longer
    exist in the game), and I realize the dilemma I put you in. However, that
    being said, and given you statements above, dont I deserve the benefit of
    the doubt especially when it might cost you my account (dont want to take
    the time to re-equip my level 53 warrior) and maybe even my future
    business?]</i></font><br>
    <br>
    I understand your prediciment, however we are limited to the duration of our
    logs, and what we know to be true. In this case, any time you give your
    login information to someone else, you are essentially giving them
    permission to take your stuff. Its roughly the same as if you had handed the
    items off yourself. Though we dont have the logs going back six months to
    see when the items were taken, the information youve given is enough to see
    that we couldnt do a reimbursement for the sake of the integrity of the
    gaming environment. We cant allow the duplication of items to be as simple
    as giving out your account info out then contacting a GM for replacement.<br>
    <br>
    Had we the logs for when your stuff disappeared, we could certainly track
    down the recipient of your belongings and take action against them. We could
    then give you back anything that we recovered from the offending party. In
    this case, we know that the items still exist, and cant just duplicate them
    given the information youve provided.<br>
    <br>
    Im sorry that we couldnt help you in this matter.<br>
    <br>
    <br>
